body: If this kid at the Stark Expo was Peter Parker, who was there with him? I mean, I am absolutely positive that whoever it was was going crazy trying to find him in the confusion. Did May and Ben have custody of him at this point, or were his parents still alive? Do you think it is possible that one or both of his parents died in the battle there? Maybe that is why May was “not a fan” of Tony Stark.

summary: Caught this over the weekend for the very first time. I’m not usually a big superhero kinda guy, especially now in the age of...
caption: Caught this over the weekend for the very first time. I’m not usually a big superhero kinda guy, especially now in the age of overblown and interconnected epics, but this movie has a lot of heart and, I’m very happy to say, is very deserving of the Academy Award for Best Animated Feature Film. Great visuals and storytelling, but also the first film I’ve ever seen that so perfectly captures the comic book experience and brings it to life on screen. I’ll be watching this one again and again.

summary: Peter had 10 minutes before Mysterio’s Multiverse Machine shut down. As he looked through all the portals and all the different...
body:
Peter had 10 minutes before Mysterio’s Multiverse Machine shut down. As he looked through all the portals and all the different dimensions, he thought of one person he wanted to see.

In a split second, all the portals showed Tony Stark. Some dimensions looked parallel, some completely unrecognizable. Peter’s cheeks hurt from smiling too hard, hot tears spilling uncontrollably. There was one portal that caught his eye. A universe where Iron Man did survive the snap. 

He watched through the portal’s lens as Tony played with Morgan in the yard. There was someone else there too: him. Morgan ran in circles as the other Peter Parker pretended to shoot webs while Tony cheered them on. Peter couldn’t blink. He could go in when Tony was alone. He could tell Tony that he had to come back because this Earth needed him. He needed him.

5 minutes before the machine powered down. Peter stayed silent, his breath hitching as the other Peter laughed at something Tony said. Why didn’t he get this happy ending? What did they do wrong? 2 minutes.

Peter slid his hands in his pockets, rummaging for a tissue. Instead, he found Tony’s black sunglasses. Happy’s voice echoed in his mind: “I don’t think Tony would’ve done what he did if he didn’t know that you were gonna be here after he was gone.” 1 minute. 

He put on the sunglasses, his face still wet. “See you later Tony.” He croaked. Zero. The machine shut down for the last time— the portals blacking out. The room returned to its previous dark and gloomy state.

As he walked outside, the battle finally over, he decided to head back to his hotel. He marveled at the multiple Iron Man murals, being careful not to step on the various clusters of candles, and smiled at the gigantic arc reactor that powered this foreign city. Tony Stark did live in this dimension and this Peter Parker saw him everywhere.
